After the Liberal International Order
Cambridge—Many analysts believe that the liberal international order came to an end with the rise of China and the election of US President Donald Trump.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he try to revive it?
Perhaps not, but he must find some alternative.
Critics are right to point out that the American order after 1945 was neither truly global nor always very liberal.
It excluded more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and incorporated many authoritarian countries.
American hegemony is always exaggerated.
Nevertheless, the most powerful countries must lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they will not be provided — and Americans will suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example.
A realistic goal for the Biden administration should be to establish an international system based on rules, with different member states participating in handling different issues.
Would China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and 21st century, both countries were unable to balance American power, while the United States operated above sovereignty,执着于 the pursuit of liberal values.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without the approval of the UN Security Council.
It also supported a "Responsibility to Protect" resolution passed by the UN General Assembly in 2005, aimed at protecting citizens suffering from their own governments —— which the United States later used in 2011 to justify bombing Libya to protect citizens in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as post-Cold War American hubris —— for example, when the NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately led to a regime change, Russia and China felt deceived —— while defenders of the action describe it as the natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
Regardless, the growth of China's and Russia's power has more strictly limited the scope of liberal interventionist actions.
So what remains?
Russia and China emphasize the principle of sovereignty stipulated in the United Nations Charter, which states that countries can only wage war in self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the occupation of neighboring countries' territories by force has been very rare, and when it does occur, it comes at a high cost due to sanctions (as seen in Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
In addition, the Security Council frequently authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled countries, and political cooperation has successfully curbed the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This dimension of a rules-based order remains crucial.
Specifically regarding economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism had supported an unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result will lead to the decoupling of global supply chains, especially in situations where national security is threatened.
Although China complains that the US is preventing companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the US position is consistent with sovereignty claims.
After all, China has prevented the operations of Google, Facebook, and Twitter in China for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
Meanwhile, despite the current crisis, cooperation in key financial areas remains very strong.
By contrast, interdependence in the ecological field creates insurmountable barriers in the face of sovereignty, because threats are transnational.
No matter how globalization in the economic sphere is hindered, environmental globalization will continue, as it is governed by biological and physical laws, which contemporary geopolitical logic has no effect on.
The above issues threaten everyone, but no country is capable of solving them independently.
Power also has so-called positive-sum dimensions in issues such as the 2019 COVID-19 pandemic and climate change.
Under such premises, it is not enough to simply think about exercising power over others.
We must also think about the dimension of exercising power together with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization have been helpful for us and for others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological differences, this did not hinder cooperation between the United States and China.
The challenge Biden faces is whether the United States and China can cooperate in producing global public goods while competing in traditional areas of great power rivalry.
Cyberspace is a new and important issue —— because it is partly transnational, but also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has already been partially fragmented.
Rules on internet freedom of speech and privacy can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian countries.
As suggested by the Global Commission on the Stability of Cyberspace, if authoritarians also want to achieve connectivity, certain rules that prohibit tampering with the fundamental structure of the internet would also be in their interest.
However, when they use proxies to conduct information warfare or interfere in elections (practices that infringe on sovereignty), rules similar to those negotiated during the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union to limit the escalation of maritime incidents must be used to reinforce norms (although hostility in the ideological domain still exists).
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly state the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrence.
Adhering to the values of freedom in cyberspace does not mean that the United States unilaterally disarms.
On the contrary, the United States should distinguish between soft power, such as open persuasion, which is permissible, and hard power, such as secret information warfare, and the United States will certainly retaliate when the other side launches secret information warfare.
Russia and China can be allowed to publicly broadcast programs and radio, but secret acts of unification such as manipulating social media are not permitted.
Moreover, the United States will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
Public opinion polls show that the American public wants to avoid military intervention, but does not want to exit alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values ideals.
If Biden is elected, the issue he faces is not whether to restore the liberal international order.
The issue is whether America can cooperate with its core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while simultaneously cooperating with a broader range of countries to manage the rules-based international system needed to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemics, cyber attacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
